Using the same initial password for all new employees creates significant security risks that could compromise your entire organization.  

The main risks include:  
(1) Mass credential exposure - if one employee shares or writes down the password, all new accounts become vulnerable;  
(2) Lateral movement - attackers gaining the common password could access multiple employee accounts;  
(3) Delayed password changes - employees may forget or postpone changing passwords, extending the vulnerability window.  

To mitigate these risks:  
(1) Generate unique temporary passwords for each employee using a secure random password generator;  
(2) Implement mandatory password changes on first login with no bypass option;  
(3) Use multi-factor authentication (MFA) for all accounts;  
(4) Set temporary passwords to expire within 24-48 hours;  
(5) Monitor for unusual login patterns;  
(6) Consider using single sign-on (SSO) with your identity provider instead of creating separate accounts.  

The safest approach is to avoid shared credentials entirely and implement proper identity lifecycle management with unique credentials from the start.

